                           </table><center>  						<!--#beginContent#-->
  						<table align='center' cellpadding=5 width='85%'>  <tr><td class='spti2' width='100%'>PLAYER STRATEGY - RANGER</td></tr>  <tr><td width='100%' class='db'><font class='dbti'>COMMANDO COMBAT--SOLOING AT 51+</font> - <small>Dariel, Mithaniel Marr</td></tr>
  <tr><td width='100%' class='db'>Everyone knows that melee classes can't solo after 20th level or so.  Right?
<BR>
<BR>
Wrong.
<BR>
<BR>
Conventional wisdom holds that melee classes are unable to solo at high levels.  Further common thought holds rangers to be the weakest of the combat classes while in a group, due to their inability to take a pounding--and therefore to be the weakest of the combat classes.
<BR>
<BR>
Given, Warriors, Rogues, and Monks outhit us in groups and raids.  Given that Warriors, Monks, Shadow Knights and Paladins can all take a heavier pounding than we can in the average group situation.  Given that we have a somewhat limited (if often very useful) role in a group situation, in peeling NPCs from casters and in making sure mobs don't get the chance to flee--and of course we're very popular when it's time to track down some rare mob someone needs for their epic.
<BR>
<BR>
All that said though, many rangers overlook an interesting possibility: screw the group.  Lone wolf it out into the wilds and perilous dungeons and bring home your own stuff.
<BR>
<BR>
To make this kind of play possible, it's important to understand a few concepts of the solo game that differ wildly from group situations:
<BR>
<BR>
First: Whoever controls movement controls the fight, and Rangers have some of the best ability to control the tactical movement of a given mob.  In the great outdoors, not only do we have Harmony, probably the single coolest mob-splitting spell in the game, but we have access to both Snare and Root while simultaneously giving ourselves enhanced movement.  Add to that that we receive Levitate and Invisibility and you wind up with the combat class best able to move around in a given area (though undead present problems) in combination with the ability to best control where a mob goes (or doesn't go.)  Use this ability to get yourself a breather and time to heal up while the mob keeps taking damage.
<BR>
<BR>
Second:  Equipment is key.  If you don't have the right stuff, you can't wander out places by yourself.  Shore up the class weaknesses and enhance its strengths through selection of Cool Toys.
<BR>
<BR>
Third: Layers.  Think those buffs and spells don't make a big difference?  Individually, maybe not.  But when stacked up together, you can present a tough mob with formidable opposition.
<BR>
<BR>
Fourth: ARCHERY.  Think it's useless?  Think again.
<BR>
<BR>
CONTROLLING MOVEMENT is a great advantage, as are the ranger's abilities to scout out possible targets.  ALWAYS make sure your mobs are snared or ensnared.  Tolan's Gauntlets are a handy device to have on hand for fights that go longer than expected, when mana is low, or when you get surprise visitors.  So long as the mob is incredibly slow, you have the ability to bug out and leave it eating dust, outdoors, or you increase your probability of being able to gain a bit of distance and camp out in Dungeon play.
<BR>
<BR>
The second trick of controlling movement is understanding the strength of your root spells.  Beginning around 45 or so, Grasping Roots becomes a spell that slaps just about any mob you want to mess with in the face with a 10 point shot of damage and 8 ticks of standing there being chewed to death by dots and feathered with arrows.  It's cheap, it's rarely resisted and it gives you a chance to catch your breath while the monster keeps getting hurt.
<BR>
<BR>
COOL TOYS are a must for a soloing Ranger, and the first rule of Cool Toys is that Armor Class Is King.  Rangers' weak point is their comparatively low defense, and it shows.  Starting around 48 or 49, The average ranger has about 40 seconds to drop a medium-blue mob in Melee before the mob drops him.  Good AC (over 1K of it) might extend this time by as much as 100 percent.  Why is that important?  Stay tuned.
<BR>
<BR>
The second rule of Cool Toys is that Free Stuff Rocks.  Tolan's gear gives you a series of great free stuff--starting with Snare on the gauntlets, Summon Arrows on the bracers, our lowest level insect-DOT on the arms, and Superior Camo on the helm.
<BR>
<BR>
(The boots have the underwater-friendly Invigor and good AC, the pants are very rare and very expensive and the BP drops off of Trak'anon.  If you have them, you certainly don't need to be listening to me!)
<BR>
<BR>
Use the free stuff gear to make sure a mob is ALWAYS slow and ALWAYS taking damage from a DOT and if possible from arrows as well.  In combination with your cheap and reliable rooting abilities, you get the chance to rest and meditate while the monster gets to sit there being chewed apart by African Fire Ants.
<BR>
<BR>
The third rule of Cool Toys says that Regeneration Is Your Friend.  Invest in a Iksar BP or in a Fungi Scaled Tunic.  Either one lets you rapidly recover HP while kiting or rooting a mob and using it for target practice, and reduces downtime to the length of time it takes you to get mana back for blasting.
<BR>
<BR>
The last rule of Cool Toys says 'Have a great weapon.'  Lamentations and Defiances are cool, but they're best left for gangbanging sluggers.  Fighting solo, you don't care about taunts, so get something that does great damage.  A Swarmcaller hits reasonably hard and cuts the enemy's damage potential in half.  A Wurmslayer remains one of the best damage ratio 1-hand weapons around, and if you pair it with a Velium Swiftblade at 50+ look out bad guys.
<BR>
<BR>
Learn about the effectiveness of LAYERS.  Rangers come with a full gamut of buffs, a couple of debuffs, and there aren't any of them that aren't useful.  The most important thing you have going for you are our DAMAGE SHIELDS.  Use them in every fight, period.  If your damage shield goes down, break off melee until you can get it back.  Damage shield makes the mob pay to hurt you.  Imagine if some poor slob of a warrior got told 'hey, you get to take a free shot at a mob that hits you with that offhand Lamentation of yours every time the mob hits you, in addition to all of your other melee abilities and you hit for max damage every time.'  Woo! would scream the warrior.  Well, you get that, ranger.  Starting at 50th, your damage shield caps out at 20 points per hit, and will probably wind up doing almost as much damage as the rest of you does in hand-to-hand.  Use it.
<BR>
<BR>
Don't underestimate your own Strength and Agility buffs, or the usefulness of Immolate--a spell that not only does twice as much damage as the DOT from the Tolan's Vambraces, but drops the Mob's AC by 10 or 12 points as well.  Think that makes no difference?  Give it a chance.  It does.
<BR>
<BR>
The new line of Call spells is very cool.  No, they aren't the most overwhelming things alive, but they give you free extra damage and that never sucks.
<BR>
<BR>
Everyone underestimates ARCHERY.  Archery is bread and butter while taking on business-class blue mobs.  If you haven't scored a Tolan's Bracer by now, either get one or get yourself a bunch of 10-slot packs and fill them with arrows.  Score a Fleeting Quiver if you can, and get a decent bow soonest.  Aim higher than a Trueshot, ranger, cause that dinky tinkertoy is beneath your dignity.
<BR>
<BR>
The key thing to remember about Archery is that quantity is, in this instance, more important than quality.  Don't spend 5 plat on a stack of damage 5 arrows that might be magic and might crit well, but which typically only hit for another 10 or 12 points of damage over normal arrows.  Spend five plat on twenty five STACKS of dinky vendor arrows and make it your mission in life to turn any mob who you aren't cutting to chutney into a walking pincushion.  
<BR>
<BR>
You might also practice Zen archery: shoot and med at the same time.  This involves lots of 'click stand, shoot, click sit down until bow reloads'.  You don't reduce your archery speed by much, and you get half-speed medding done while you're doing it.
<BR>
<BR>
Once you realize the kind of damage you can dish out (at 51 with only a Bow of the Huntsman and no haste items of any kind I could average about 35 points per tick--a DOT more effective than both my spell-based DOTS put together, at no mana cost), you may find it well worth your while to play with archery.  Upcoming Archery-buff spells in the Luclin expansion may make this practice even more cooler than it already is.
<BR>
<BR>
So, here are the basic tactics you use, following the principal of a commando fighter--hit the enemy with everything you have, bug out before he can kill you, and come back again when you're stronger.
<BR>
<BR>
Open up with a Root.  Ensnare.  DOT, DOT, and damage shield yourself.  Some variation in order may be necessary.  Close to melee while your Immolate lowers the mob's AC.  Melee until Immolate expires, or until your HPs are alarmingly low.  Root the mob, back off of him, and hang around slapping him with free DOTs and insultingly cheap arrows.  Once you've healed and/or regenerated up to a better state of health, Immolate him again and close in to continue pounding (and letting him slam himself silly against your damage shield).
<BR>
<BR>
This tactic can beat tough mobs, even named quest mobs--though be warned, it can take a while.  (I killed one of the named Wurms in a two-hour session of kiting one slow evening.)  In less extreme circumstances, though, it is a lot more reasonable.  I was pulling Chief RyGorr from a full fort at 51 and soloing him.  It took about 10 minutes to kill him, but it was fun the whole time and I got to walk away with several Spine Chill Spears and RyGorr battle mail over the course of a week.
<BR>
<BR>
Good hunting sites that I've found so far (low 50s) include Eastern Wastes, where there are always a few blue mobs, many of them animals and subject to our fear spell.  Crystal Cavern is a fun place, since our track lets us move right to the rare mobs to execute them for their stuff--be sure not to poach something being camped by lower levels.  Spirocs in Timorous Deep, on Ogre Island, give great XP and can be fought easily in singles and with minimal risk.  About 12 hours of fighting there took me through 3 yellow bubs of 51st level xp.  City of Mist is an incredibly fun place to solo, though I wouldn't recommend it below 50.  There are a few green mobs mixed in, but there are several sites where you can fight mostly low blues who can be soloed without needing to get fancy, and a couple of places where you can take on tougher mobs in a limited kiting environment--and gives you a shot at rare drop treasure.  Emerald Jungle always has a lot of blues that can be hunted down, and Wakening Lands has caves full of Geonids that can be kited if one is careful.  Those boys drop nifty gems and so forth, too.  Cobalt Scar wyverns are doable (as long as the Druids don't have them all), as are Seafuries in OOT.  Burning Woods is a good spot, and if you are VERY careful and practice, you can do some limited soloing in the Skyfire Mountains.
<BR>
<BR>
Give it a shot, rangers, just for variety.  You are one of the most flexible and resourceful classes in the game of EQ, and don't let anyone tell you differently.  If you get bored with good xp and keeping EVERY piece of loot that you see drop, you can always join up with a group just for the variety. :)</td></tr>
  <tr><td class='db'>&nbsp;</td></tr>
  <tr><td class='db'>Strategy Submitted on: Monday, December 17, 2001</td></tr>
